\begin_layout Abstract
To start with, this is not so much needs as it is about asset-bearing costs.
 The mention of needs should be done with respect to assets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Utility and Intertemporal Substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest instance of intertemporal substitution is a two period model
 where assets are meant to be liquidated at the end of the second period.
 If one may assume that the relative preference of quality over assets does
 not change over time, the utility to be optimised by the consumer in the
 two-period model can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
U & =\beta_{1}(a\ log(\nu_{1})+b\ log(A_{1}))+\beta_{2}(a\ log(\nu_{2})+b\ log(A_{2}))
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 are consumption on quality in periods 1 and 2 while 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

 are that on assets in the respective periods (assuming that needs do not
 carry utility )
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An alternate equivalent form may be more intuitive 
\begin_inset Formula $U=a(\beta_{1}log(\nu_{1})+\beta_{2}log(\nu_{2}))+b(\beta_{1}log(A_{1})+\beta_{2}log(A_{2}))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the typical solution of the intertemporal problem, the wealth constraint
 could be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\frac{A_{2}}{(1+r)^{2}}+\frac{c_{1}-p_{1}}{1+r}+\frac{c_{2}-p_{2}}{(1+r)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 so that Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L=U-\lambda(W-\frac{A_{2}}{(1+r)^{2}}-\frac{c_{1}-p_{1}}{1+r}-\frac{c_{2}-p_{2}}{(1+r)^{2}})$
\end_inset

 leads to the first order conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial L}{\partial\nu_{1}}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\nu_{2}}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\lambda}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Notice however that one cannot guarantee 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial f(\nu_{2})}{\partial\nu_{1}}=0$
\end_inset

 in the for the optimisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 This is where the boundary condition of the final asset state being 0 (i.e.
 all of the consumer's assets being liquidated and consumed in the last
 period) and a discount factor for expected state (whose Euler equations
 are specified) help simplify the optimisation problem
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This solution a the non-stochastic intertemporal problem essentially draws
 an equivalence between total wealth constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and the total outlay 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i}p_{i}q_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the classical consumer choice problem ) before employing similar econometric
 methods.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\beta ln(x)+\gamma ln(p)+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 commonly used in estimation is effectively derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=p_{i}q_{i}/x\Rightarrow log(w_{i})=log(p_{i})+log(g(x,p))-log(x)$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,p)$
\end_inset

 as the Marshallian demand function, using the double-logarithmic model
 (which is a mere restatement of existence of elasticities through total
 differentiation) yields 
\begin_inset Formula $log(g(x,p))=\alpha_{i}+\frac{\partial log(g(x,p))}{\partial log(x)}log(x)+\frac{\partial log(g(x,p))}{\partial log(p)}log(p)$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $log(w_{i})=\alpha_{i}+(\frac{\partial log(g(x,p))}{\partial log(x)}-1)log(x)+(\frac{\partial log(g(x,p))}{\partial log(p_{i})}+1)log(p_{i})+\sum_{j\ne i}\frac{\partial log(g(x,p))}{\partial log(p_{j})}log(p_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 Since the adding up restriction is more difficult to impose on this form
 rather than the slightly modified : 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\alpha_{i}+\beta_{i}log(x)+\gamma_{i}log(p_{i})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the latter is the more popular choice.
 An estimation of demand elasticities of consumption can be performed with
 parallel arguments using the total wealth constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 In this equivalent formulation, the constraint for the consumer can be
 stated as the total wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\delta_{i}(A_{T}+\sum c_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{T}$
\end_inset

 are the assets accumulated over the period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and the discount factors can be chosen as
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i}=\frac{1}{1+i}$
\end_inset

 (this holds even if one assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{T}$
\end_inset

 is 0 at the end by the consumer spending everything as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{T}$
\end_inset

 at the end of period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

).
 Equivalent to the case of income constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{p}\cdot\textbf{q}=x$
\end_inset

 for the maximisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(\textbf{q})$
\end_inset

, the wealth constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is meant to be known to the representative consumer i.e.
 the consumer chooses a plan for 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i},A_{i}$
\end_inset

 knowing what her total wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and future expectations of prices are.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since we consider the final state of assets exogenous in our model, we
 take a slightly different approach with the formulation of a dynamic optimisati
on problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the initial and final asset levels known, the Euler equations can be
 written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
A_{t+1} & =A_{t}(1+r)+i_{t+1}-\nu_{t+1}-\Psi_{t+1}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above signifies that the consumer may consume quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{3...}$
\end_inset

 being undefined) in the periods 1 and 2 while she bears the cost of the
 needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 (in periods 1 and 2 respectively).
 The intertemporal substitution setting means that she may save for asset
 growth to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of consuming all her income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=\nu_{t}+\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 she can spend all her income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1},i_{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) or save some of it towards 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If initial conditions are 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset

 (the starting wealth), the rate of growth of money (interest rate) and
 an exogenous income process 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 are known, we can expand the the Euler equations as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
A_{1}=A_{0}(1+r)+i_{1}-c_{1}=A_{0}(1+r)+i_{1}-\Psi_{1}-\nu_{1}\\
(\because c_{1}=\Psi_{1}+\nu_{1})
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
A_{2} & =A_{1}(1+r)+i_{2}-\Psi_{2}-\nu_{2}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

 Assuming that we observe both states of the wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 we can then to solve for the parameters that govern the utility function
 additive over time 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1},u_{2}$
\end_inset

 are utilities over periods and 1 and 2 (respectively).
 To motivate the dynamic optimisation approach, consider the consumer's
 choices in a one-period consumption - where she could either spend all
 income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{_{1}}=\nu_{1}+\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 or keep the minimum consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0,c_{1}=\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

) in the period and end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, then the first-order conditions would provide us the optimal condition
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this utility be 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}^{*},A_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To extend this to two periods with dynamic optimisation one can exploit
 the fact that a consumer independently optimising 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 would always obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 are unbounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $max(u_{1}+u_{2})\le max(u_{1})+max(u_{2})=u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 is only a tool to formulate the dynamic optimisation approach - using which
 the expected value of utility is to be optimised over her life period in
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-period model (
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being the age of the consumer).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The changes in expected utility per period are what drive her behaviour
 at every period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and her choice is set to vary according to her age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (assuming that all consumers have similar expectations for the trajectory
 of their needs).
 A steady state would thus be achieved with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 over all ages.
 The conditions of stability of the steady state imply that while consumers
 maintain different 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 , they are a function of characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

and age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the notion that a consumer may change her behaviour away from the
 current plan in the future is fallacious since a consumer observed at different
 ages is equivalent to consumers of varied ages at any point in time (see
 Deaton's clarification of the so-called dynamic inconsistency problem 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Understanding Consumption
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In other words, the behaviour of an older consumer is the same as the future
 behaviour of a younger consumer.
 So the optimal solution for the total sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{T-t}u_{i}$
\end_inset

 would apply both to the individuals of all ages as well as an individuals
 over a number of years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
>>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Peer effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the preference of assets vs quality does not change over time,
 consider the inclusion of personal characteristics in the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sum_{t}\beta_{t}(\upsilon_{t})$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\upsilon_{t} & =a\ log(A_{t})+b\ log(\nu_{i})+(1-a-b)log(\rho)\label{eq:utility_with_rho}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows the the consumer to compensate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 More educated people (or those with higher percieved class) might need
 less assets and less quality.
 On the other hand, due to the high upfront cost attached to owning assets,
 there may be a certain levelling effect to how much assets can be used
 to compensate for not having the best 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

- a limiting factor that would lead to the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 dominating the choice for the consumer.
 The ownership of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is thus likely to be segregated over a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 In the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:utility_with_rho"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 or its equivalent formulations, an influential 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has two competing roles for the consumer utility - first, it allows the
 consumer to not require so much assets.
 Second, it requires the consumer to maintain a certain level that is required
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 she possesses.
 This interplay of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 is indeed how peer effects - the claim that the consumer considers quality
 relative to her reference group rather than an absolute level enter the
 model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If peer effects were to be modeled explicitly, let's say through a distance
 from average 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 calculated over 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (or a belonging to an ordinal class - see Chai), then as long as the higher
 status rank (part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) are also wealthy, the consumer with a high status rank due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 would also need to keep up the quality consumption to her wealthier reference
 level.
 Therefore, those in the higher rank (e.g.
 higher status occupations etc.) would benefit both from being in a higher
 status group (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) and from the higher asset possession that entails being in the high status
 group (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

).
 To avoid double-accounting for the effect that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 has on the utility, we choose only the characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that form the reference group over which the distance from average consumption
 is considered relevant for peer effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some recent literature has found an ordinal treatment of status more suitable
 for modeling status-related consumption.
 We believe that the properties of the average over the chosen personal
 characteristic - allows us to consider an ordinal treatment without losing
 the tractability of averages in estimation.
 If we are sure to consider only the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that can serve as a reference group for consumption, then the presence
 of peer effects only means that the consumer does not worry about having
 less 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 than the average of a community (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 ) she does not consider herself a member of.
 Instead, the utility derived by being ahead of the local average (of quality
 or assets) i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is more significant to her.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider a market of just quality (and no assets) as an illustration.
 Here, a model for utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $S=a\nu+b\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu$
\end_inset

 which is similar to the Ireland's signaling model - in the sense that the
 utility is a combination of private and public sub-utilities.
 The decomposition of the model as 
\begin_inset Formula $S=a\nu+b\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu=a(\nu-\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu)+(a+b)\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu)$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as how the total utility can be seen as a combination
 of the sub-utility from the distance in quality from the local average
 and that from the overall effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 This interpretation permits us to approximate the second term with a function
 solely of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 while the first term with a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer thus maintains both a relative advantage and the collective
 absolute advantage from quality - without issues of double-accounting.
 The approach would not change if difference in assets were introduced in
 the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that the measurement of distance from needs or 
\shape italic
excess
\shape default
 - which we track with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is no direct measure of peer effects.
 The distance from needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 in fact only encompasses the higher price of the items or their consumed
 quantity.
 As such 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is reflects spatial variation in prices as well and thus the controls for
 spatial variation must be included in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 over which peer effects are considered.
 More generally, the characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 that may serve as an appropriate cluster over which 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}f_{\nu}d\nu$
\end_inset

 is evaluated are driven by the particular dataset at hand.
 Out of the characteristics like region, occupation or education, one may
 be more important than the others rest in a particular context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we introduce the assets in the model, the Euler equations of the intertempora
l setting allow us to model to what extent the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 may move together with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

.Towards the goal of viewing the relative preference of quality with respect
 to asset ownership, the intertemporal setting prevents an assumption of
 comovement of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 (on the lines of the permanent income approach).
 Finally, therefore the model we use has the following utility function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u_{\tau}(\tau,\rho) & =a_{\tau}log(\Psi_{\tau})+b_{\rho}log(A_{\tau})+(1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho})log(\nu_{\tau})
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the age of the household.
 The model relies on the assumption that the utility factor for quality
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

) changes both with age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, the utility factor for needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

) changes with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (not with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

) and the factor for assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

) changes only with characteristics.
 The last assumption rests upon the definition of assets being intergenerational
 (and thus long-term enough for their utility to change over time).
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is used to signify that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 does not change with personal characteristics the way 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 does not change with age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 The utility that the consumer gets from from the same level of quality
 and assets would vary with both personal characteristics (reference group)
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, but due to the very definition of needs, the total cost of needs does
 not vary with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 signifies the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}\nu d\nu$
\end_inset

 it also encompasses the peer effects arising out of the reference group
 identity.
 Also worth remembering is that any non-durable consumption other than what
 is driven by the assets and the basic-needs would constitute any status-related
 consumption.
 The relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

is made explicit with the Euler equations for the intertemporal setting:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
A_{\tau+1}=A_{\tau}(1+r)+i_{\tau+1}-c_{\tau+1}\label{eq:mar2020_euler}\\
c_{\tau+1}=\nu_{\tau+1}+\Psi_{\tau+1}\nonumber 
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the income process 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

 is a exogenous process that may be function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The first-order conditions imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u_{\tau+1}}{\partial\nu_{\tau+1}}=0\Rightarrow\frac{b_{\rho}}{A_{\tau+1}}\frac{\partial A_{\tau+1}}{\partial\nu_{\tau+1}}=-\frac{1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho}}{\nu_{\tau+1}}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau+1}=\frac{1-a_{\tau}-b_{\rho}}{b_{\rho}}A_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

 .
 If we observe 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau+1}$
\end_inset

, the following equation is useful for estimation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

